			<div class="content">
								<article class="entry post-11938 post type-post status-publish hentry tag-bush-jeb tag-cruz-ted tag-democratic-party tag-law-and-legislation tag-menendez-robert tag-reid-harry per-bush-jeb per-cruz-ted per-menendez-robert per-reid-harry des-law-and-legislation org-democratic-party news_keywords-democrats news_keywords-harry-reid news_keywords-jeb-bush news_keywords-legislation news_keywords-robert-menendez news_keywords-ted-cruz" id="post-11938">
					<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="inline-module-container show-on-viewport-medium">
	<div class="inlineModule byline">
		<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-04-02T11:09:18+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">7:09 <span class="seg">am ET</span></time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">7:09 <span class="seg">am ET</span></span>    		<div class="name" data-author="By The New York Times">
    			<address class="author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
								<span class="fn">By The New York Times</span>
							</address>
		</div>
		<div class="shareTools sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet" data-url="//www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/04/02/today-in-politics-indiana-law-deepens-strain-between-republicans-and-business/" data-title="Today in Politics: Indiana Law Deepens Strain Between Republicans and Business" data-description="An Indiana law has become a thorn for Republicans, especially in their dealings with business leaders."></div>	</div>
</div><h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title"><a href="//www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/04/02/today-in-politics-indiana-law-deepens-strain-between-republicans-and-business/" rel="bookmark" class="entry-title-link " title="Permanent link to Today in Politics: Indiana Law Deepens Strain Between Republicans and Business">Today in Politics: Indiana Law Deepens Strain Between Republicans and Business</a></h1>	<div class="hide-on-viewport-medium byline">
		<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-04-02T11:09:18+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">7:09 <span class="seg">am ET</span></time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">7:09 <span class="seg">am ET</span></span>		<div class="name" data-author="By The New York Times" >
			<span class="author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By <address class="vcard first-byline" itemscope itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person" itemid="The New York Times">
					<span class="fn" itemprop="name">The New York Times</span>
				</address>			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="shareTools sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet" data-url="//www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/04/02/today-in-politics-indiana-law-deepens-strain-between-republicans-and-business/" data-title="Today in Politics: Indiana Law Deepens Strain Between Republicans and Business" data-description="An Indiana law has become a thorn for Republicans, especially in their dealings with business leaders."></div>	</div>
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/04/02/us/politics/02firstdraft-newsletter-religious-freedom/02firstdraft-newsletter-religious-freedom-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/04/02/us/politics/02firstdraft-newsletter-religious-freedom/02firstdraft-newsletter-religious-freedom-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/04/02/us/politics/02firstdraft-newsletter-religious-freedom/02firstdraft-newsletter-religious-freedom-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003606588" width="592" height="395" alt="Demonstrators gathered on the steps of the Arkansas State Capitol in Little Rock on Tuesday."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Demonstrators gathered on the steps of the Arkansas State Capitol in Little Rock on Tuesday.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Andrea Morales/Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Good Thursday morning from Washington, where <strong>Senator Robert Menendez</strong>âs corruption charges are already becoming a political problem for Democrats. <strong>President Obama</strong> is heading to Kentucky to talk about the economy, while <strong>Speaker John A. Boehner</strong> wraps up his big international trip. <strong>Jeb Bush</strong> seems to have modified his response to an Indiana law seen as both a protection of religious freedom and an invitation for discrimination, while the law </em><em>has <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/02/us/rights-measures-expose-divisions-in-gops-ranks.html?hp&amp;action=click&amp;pgtype=Homepage&amp;module=first-column-region&amp;region=top-news&amp;WT.nav=top-news" rel="nofollow">become a thorn for Republicans</a>, especially in their dealings with business leaders.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Walmart, Apple, Eli Lilly and General Electric may be vastly different companies, but they have at least one thing in common: opposition to the Republican-backed legislation described by proponents as religious freedom laws that have brought a backlash to Indiana and Arkansas.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">With likely Republican presidential candidates having lined up to support state versions of the Religious Freedom Restoration Act, the issue is likely to persist through 2016 in debates and campaign ads. But more worrying to Republicans may be the overt resistance from corporate America, a traditionally loyal constituency and source of donations.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The legislation creates the latest rift between Republicans and large businesses after frustration surrounding the &#8220;fiscal cliff&#8221; face-off, the government shutdown and immigration battles that many executives say harmed the economy. With corporate workforces becoming younger and more progressive, platforms of low taxes and less regulation are not enough to appease anymore.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Jeffrey R. Immelt</strong>, the chief executive of General Electric and a frequent Republican donor, <a href="//www.ge.com/sites/default/files/jeff_immelt_letter_to_governor_pence.pdf" rel="nofollow">was the latest to write to <strong>Gov. Mike Pence </strong>of Indiana</a>, arguing on Wednesday that the law could harm his workers and that the company does not tolerate discrimination.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Cook Medical, which was founded by the billionaire <strong>Gayle Cook</strong>, a big Republican donor in Indiana, also pressured Mr. Pence, saying on Facebook, â<a href="https://www.facebook.com/cookmedical/posts/380836215440686" rel="nofollow">We value diversity at all levels.â</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Walmartâs foray into a social issue and its <a href="https://mobile.twitter.com/walmartnewsroom/status/583032659787448320" rel="nofollow">call for <strong>Gov. Asa Hutchinson</strong> of Arkansas to veto his stateâs bill</a> was the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/02/business/walmart-emerges-as-unlikely-social-force.html?hp&amp;action=click&amp;pgtype=Homepage&amp;module=photo-spot-region&amp;region=top-news&amp;WT.nav=top-news" rel="nofollow">most surprising</a>. <strong>Jim Walton</strong>, a son of the companyâs founder, <a href="https://www.opensecrets.org/indivs/search.php?sort=D&amp;name=Jim%2BWalton&amp;state=&amp;zip=&amp;employ=&amp;cand=&amp;soft=&amp;cycle=All" rel="nofollow">donated thousands of dollars</a> to the National Republican Senatorial Committee, the Republican Party of Arkansas and <strong>Senator Tom Cotton</strong> last year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As the legislation shakes out, Democrats are unlikely to let go.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âYouâre going to have <strong>Chuck Schumer</strong> and others talking turkey to members of the business community and asking them to think about whatâs really in their interest and the interest of their investors,â said <strong>Thomas E. Mann</strong>, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution, referring to the Democratic senator from New York.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>&#8212; Alan Rappeport</em></p>
<h4 id="post-mb-2" class="entry-title" style="font-size: 16px; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px;"><a class="nyt-dynamic-url" href="#post-mb-2" rel="bookmark">What We&#8217;re Watching Today</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>President Obama</strong> travels to Louisville, Ky., for an event that the local news media says will be about job training. He will then travel to Utah for the first time as president, his 49th state.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Janet L. Yellen</strong>, the Federal Reserve chairwoman, who <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/28/business/yellen-says-fed-will-increase-rates-slowly.html?ref=topics" rel="nofollow">said last month</a> that the Fed would raise interest rates slowly because of the economy&#8217;s fragile condition, will speak at a Fed conference in the morning.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Also in the morning, the Labor Department will release weekly unemployment numbers.</p>
<h4 id="post-mb-3" class="entry-title" style="font-size: 16px; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px;"><a class="nyt-dynamic-url" href="#post-mb-3" rel="bookmark">Republicans Seek to Use Menendez Against Democrats</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Republicans wasted little time trying to turn <strong>Senator Robert Menendez </strong>of New Jersey into a liability for other Democrats.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Shortly after criminal corruption charges were announced against Mr. Menendez, the National Republican Senatorial Committee set its sights on <strong>Senator Michael Bennet </strong>of Colorado. Mr. Bennet received a $10,000 donation from Mr. Menendez, and the committee said the money should be returned.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âColoradans expect the highest ethical conduct from their representatives in Washington, and Senator Bennet has clearly had a lapse in judgment when it comes to Senator Menendez,â <strong>Matt Connelly</strong>, the group&#8217;s spokesman, said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/07/us/menendez-expected-to-face-federal-corruption-charges.html" rel="nofollow">reports surfaced</a> last month that Mr. Menendez would face charges, Republicans also sought to put the spotlight on donations he gave to <strong>Senator Patty Murray </strong>of Washington and <strong>Representative Chris Van Hollen</strong> of Maryland, arguing that they, too, should give back money Mr. Menendez had given them through his New Millennium political action committee.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The group also tried to make Mr. Menendez a political problem for <strong>Senator Harry Reid</strong> of Nevada, challenging him to follow his policy on returning donations from people indicted for criminal charges.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Now that Mr. Reid, <a href="//www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2013/02/senate_majority_leader_harry_r.html" rel="nofollow">who has previously defended Mr. Menendez</a>, is planning to retire at the end of his term, heâs unlikely to be too worried about the politics of the situation.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Wednesday evening, Mr. Reid&#8217;s office <a href="//www.reid.senate.gov/press_releases/2015-4-1-reid-statement-on-senator-menendez" rel="nofollow">issued a statement</a> praising Mr. Menendez: &#8220;He has been a consistent champion for the middle class. As I have said about both Democrats and Republicans, our justice system is premised on the principle of innocent until proven guilty, and Senator Menendez should not be judged until he has his day in court.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>&#8212; Alan Rappeport</em></p>
<h4 id="post-mb-4" class="entry-title" style="font-size: 16px; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px;"><a class="nyt-dynamic-url" href="#post-mb-4" rel="bookmark">In Israel, Boehner and Netanyahu Tone It Down</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Speaker John A. Boehner</strong> wrapped up an international trip that managed to be both high profile for his stop in Israel and low key for his muted remarks alongside <strong>Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. </strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As negotiations over a possible nuclear deal with Iran continued to stretch on, Mr. Boehner, who had provoked an uproar by inviting Mr. Netanyahu to address Congress last month, did not mention Iran. He instead made generic comments like âthe bonds between the United States and Israel <a href="//www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/04/01/verbatim-boehner-pledges-strong-bond-with-israel/" rel="nofollow">are as strong as ever,</a>â despite occasional political disagreements. Mr. Netanyahu&#8217;s language also seemed notably toned down.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The approach suggested Mr. Boehner didnât see Israel as the appropriate site to further challenge <strong>President Obama</strong> over Iran. It also reflected a maxim that members of Congress have traditionally followed on official trips overseas: If youâre making big news, you&#8217;re doing it wrong.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>&#8212; Carl Hulse</em></p>
<h4 id="post-mb-5" class="entry-title" style="font-size: 16px; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px;"><a class="nyt-dynamic-url" href="#post-mb-5" rel="bookmark">Bulletins: Bush Shifts Tone; Cruz Keeps His; Clinton Nods to Past</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Former Gov. Jeb Bush</strong> of Florida seemed <a href="//www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/04/01/bush-seems-to-shift-tone-in-his-praise-of-indiana-law/" rel="nofollow">to modify his assessment</a> of <strong>Gov. Mike Pence</strong>&#8216;s handling of a law in Indiana that some say is a matter of religious freedom, and that others say is potentially discriminatory.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Senator Ted Cruz</strong> of Texas <a href="//www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/04/01/cruz-in-iowa-commends-indiana-for-doing-the-right-thing/?module=BlogPost-Title&amp;version=Blog%20Main&amp;contentCollection=Politics&amp;action=Click&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Body" rel="nofollow">did not </a>seem to modify his assessment of the Indiana law.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Hillary Rodham Clinton</strong> <a href="//www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/04/01/in-a-nod-to-past-and-future-clinton-pushes-child-development-in-brooklyn/" rel="nofollow">joined a panel</a> in Brooklyn with <strong>Chirlane McCray</strong>, the wife of <strong>Mayor Bill de Blasio</strong> of New York, to discuss early childhood development, an issue she has advocated since her years at Yale Law School.</p>
<h4 id="post-mb-7" class="entry-title" style="font-size: 16px; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px;"><a class="nyt-dynamic-url" href="#post-mb-7" rel="bookmark">Our Favorites From Today&#8217;s Times</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Senator Robert Menendez </strong>of New Jersey <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/02/nyregion/senator-robert-menendez-indicted-on-corruption-charges.html" rel="nofollow">was indicted</a> on corruption charges.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Senator Harry Reid said that <strong>Jeb Bush</strong> <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/03/us/harry-reid-hopes-to-ensure-democrats-success-as-tenure-winds-down.html?smprod=nytcore-iphone&amp;smid=nytcore-iphone-share" rel="nofollow">would be the easiest opponent</a> for <strong>Hillary Rodham Clinton</strong> in a presidential race.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Measures in Indiana and Arkansas <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/02/us/rights-measures-expose-divisions-in-gops-ranks.html" rel="nofollow">expose divisions</a> in the Republican ranks.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The son of <strong>Gov. Asa Hutchinson</strong> of Arkansas <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/02/us/arkansas-governors-son-thurst-into-spotlight-over-religious-freedom-bill.html" rel="nofollow">is thrust into the spotlight</a> over the state&#8217;s religious exception bill.</p>
<h4 id="post-mb-8" class="entry-title" style="font-size: 16px; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px;"><a class="nyt-dynamic-url" href="#post-mb-8" rel="bookmark">What We&#8217;re Reading Elsewhere</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>President Obama</strong> <a href="https://medium.com/@PresidentObama/a-new-tool-against-cyber-threats-1a30c188bc4" rel="nofollow">writes</a> in Medium about the cyberattack threats that prompted his push for new measures to combat them.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Washington Post <a href="//www.washingtonpost.com/news/acts-of-faith/wp/2015/04/01/10-things-you-need-to-know-to-really-understand-rfra-in-indiana-and-arkansas/?tid=sm_tw" rel="nofollow">offers</a> &#8220;10 Things You Need to Know to Really Understand&#8221; the Indiana and Arkansas controversy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Politico says the Indiana law <a href="//www.politico.com/magazine/story/2015/04/mike-pence-indiana-2016-116569.html?hp=t2_r#.VRyillyKpRo" rel="nofollow">has damaged</a> <strong>Gov. Mike Pence</strong>&#8216;s presidential aspirations.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Former <strong>President Richard M. Nixon&#8217;</strong>s <a href="//www.ocregister.com/articles/herbert-656409-nixon-estate.html" rel="nofollow">&#8220;Western White House&#8221; is for sale for $75 million</a>, The Orange County Register reports.</p>
